</ref> The burial coincided with a ceremony to mark the opening of the Yagan Memorial Park which was attended by around 300 people, including Noongar elders and State government representatives.<ref name="au-news-yahoo-com" /> [[Premier of Western Australia|State Premier]] [[Colin Barnett]] described the occasion as "a wonderful day for all West Australians."<ref name="au-news-yahoo-com" />

The art works for the Yagan Memorial Park were designed by Peter Farmer, Sandra Hill, Jenny Dawson and Kylie Ricks.<ref>{{cite web|url = http://monumentaustralia.org.au/themes/people/indigenous/display/93059-yagan-memorial-park |date=2010 |work=Monument Australia |title = Yagan Memorial Park | accessdate =4 November 2015}}</ref> Dawson and Hill created an entry wall of Yagan's story; Farmer designed the park entry statements and Ricks the [[Coolamon (vessel)|female Coolamon]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.artsource.net.au/Consulting/client-services/Public-Art-Procurement/Yagan-Memorial-Park|title=Yagan Memorial Park|work=Artsource|accessdate=4 November 2015}}</ref>

==Legacy==
The repatriation of Yagan's head increased the Aboriginal leader's notability. He is considered a famous historical figure throughout Australia,{{sfn|Fforde|2002|p=234}} with material about him appearing in such publications as the ''[[Australian Dictionary of Biography]]'',<ref name="ADB">{{Australian Dictionary of Biography | last = Hasluck | first = Alexandra | authorlink = Alexandra Hasluck |year= 1967|title =Yagan ( – 1833)| id = A020578b.htm | accessdate =6 March 2008}}</ref> and Western Australia's school [[curriculum]].<ref name="CCoWA">{{cite web | title = Aboriginal and intercultural studies | url = http://newwace.curriculum.wa.edu.au/docs/COS_docs/171791_7_1.pdf |format=PDF| publisher=[[Curriculum Council of Western Australia]] | accessdate =6 March 2008|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080411053559/http://newwace.curriculum.wa.edu.au/docs/COS_docs/171791_7_1.pdf |archivedate = 11 April 2008|deadurl=yes}}</ref> He is of greatest significance, however, to the Noongar people,{{sfn|Fforde|2002|p=234}} for whom he is "a revered, cherished and heroic individual&nbsp;... patriot and visionary hero of WA's South-West".<ref name="Colbung 1996">{{cite book|author=Colbung, Ken|year=1996|title=Yagan: The Swan River "Settlement"|publisher=Australia Council for the Arts|authorlink=Ken Colbung}}</ref> The return of his head was likened by some Indigenous Australians to the November 1993 ceremonial repatriation from [[Gallipoli]] of Australia's [[Tomb of the Unknown Soldier|unknown soldier]].<ref name="Human Rights and Equal Opportunity Commission 2001">[[Human Rights and Equal Opportunity Commission]] (2001). ''Corunna v West Australian Newspapers'' (2001) EOC 93–146. 12 April 2001.</ref>

The former Upper Swan Bridge, which carries the [[Great Northern Highway]] over the Swan River at [[Belhus, Western Australia|Belhus]], was renamed the Yagan Bridge in 2010.<ref>''"In tribute to the famous Aboriginal warrior, Yagan, the Upper Swan Bridge was renamed the Yagan Bridge in 2010."''. [http://www.swan.wa.gov.au/Lists/Suburbs/Upper_Swan In My Area – Upper Swan] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140703123200/http://www.swan.wa.gov.au/Lists/Suburbs/Upper_Swan |date=3 July 2014 }} – City of Swan. Retrieved 5 June 2014.</ref> Also, an open plaza in the [[Perth (suburb)|Perth central business district]], constructed as part of the [[Perth City Link]] urban renewal project, was named [[Yagan Square]].<ref>Colleen Egan (31 May 2014). [https://au.news.yahoo.com/thewest/a/23997883/city-square-to-be-named-after-yagan/ "City square to be named after Yagan"] – ''The West Australian''. Retrieved 5 June 2014.</ref> The plaza, located adjacent to the [[Horseshoe Bridge]], was opened on 3 March 2018.<ref>[https://www.mra.wa.gov.au/news-and-updates/works-updates/market-hall-and-horseshoe-lane-construction "Market Hall and Horseshoe Lane construction"]</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2018-03-03/yagan-square-opens-in-perth/9505952|title=Perth's Yagan Square finally opens to the public|last=Cookson|first=Jasmine|date=3 March 2018|work=ABC News|access-date=25 June 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.perthnow.com.au/news/perth/yagan-square-to-open-on-march-3-ng-b88744021z|title=Yagan Square to open on March 3|last=Spagnolo|first=Joe|date=18 February 2018|work=Perth Now|access-date=25 June 2018}}</ref>

==Cultural references==

===''Alas Poor Yagan''===
{{Main article|Alas Poor Yagan}}
<!-- FAIR USE of Alas Poor Yagan (2 panels).jpg: see image description page at http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Image:Alas_Poor_Yagan_(2_panels).jpg for rationale -->
[[Image:Alas Poor Yagan (2 panels).jpg|thumb|400px|The final two frames of [[Dean Alston]]'s 1997 cartoon ''[[Alas Poor Yagan]]'']]
On 6 September 1997 ''[[The West Australian]]'' published a [[Dean Alston]] [[cartoon]] entitled ''[[Alas Poor Yagan]]'',<ref name="Alston 1997">[[Dean Alston|Alston, Dean]] (1997). [[Alas Poor Yagan]]. ''[[The West Australian]]'', 6 September 1997.</ref> which was critical of the fact that the return of Yagan's head had become a source of conflict between Noongars instead of fostering unity.<ref name="Federal Court of Australia 2004"/> The cartoon was interpreted by some as insulting aspects of Noongar culture, and casting aspersions on the motives and legitimacy of Indigenous Australians with mixed racial heritage.<ref name="Federal Court of Australia 2004"/> The content of the cartoon offended many Indigenous Australians, and a group of Noongar elders complained about the cartoon to the [[Human Rights and Equal Opportunity Commission]].<ref name="Federal Court of Australia 2004"/> The commission ruled that the cartoon made inappropriate references to Noongar beliefs but was not in breach of the [[Racial Discrimination Act 1975]] because it was "an artistic work" that was published "reasonably and in good faith", and was therefore exempt.<ref name="Human Rights and Equal Opportunity Commission 2001"/> This ruling was upheld on appeal by the [[Federal Court of Australia]],<ref name="Federal Court of Australia 2004">[[Federal Court of Australia]] (2004). [http://www.austlii.edu.au/au/cases/cth/FCAFC/2004/16.html ''Bropho v Human Rights & Equal Opportunity Commission''] 2004 FCAFC 16. 6 February 2004.</ref> Some academic commentators have since expressed concern that the protections offered under the act have been undermined by the ruling's broad interpretation of the exemptions.<ref name="McGlade 2001">{{cite journal | first = Hannah | last = McGlade | year = 2001 | title = Race Vilification Before the Human Rights and Equal Opportunity Commission | journal=[[Indigenous Law Bulletin]] | volume = 5 | issue = 7}}</ref><ref name="Chapman 2004">{{cite journal | first = Anna | last = Chapman | title = Australian Racial Hatred Law: Some Comments on Reasonableness and Adjudicative Method in Complaints Brought by Indigenous People | year = 2004 | journal=Monash University Law Review | volume = 30 | pages = 27–48}}</ref>

===Statue===
From the mid-1970s, members of the Noongar community lobbied for the erection of a [[statue]] of Yagan as part of the [[WAY 1979]] sesquicentennial celebrations. Their requests were refused, however, after then [[Premier of Western Australia]] [[Charles Court|Sir Charles Court]] was advised by one prominent historian that Yagan was not important enough to warrant a statue.<ref name="Inglis 1998">{{cite book | first = K. S. | last = Inglis | year = 1998 | title = Sacred Places | publisher=Melbourne University Press | isbn = 0-522-84976-8 | page = 448 | quote = [Hasluck] advised the states anti-Labor government not to agree. University historians pleaded Yagan's cause in vain.}}</ref> Colbung claims "Court was more interested in spending tax payers' money on refurbishing the badly neglected burial place of [[James Stirling (Australian governor)|Captain James Stirling]], WA's first governor."<ref name="Colbung 1996"/> Despite this setback, the Noongar community persisted, establishing a Yagan Committee and running a number of fund-raising drives. Eventually, sufficient funds were collected to allow the commissioning of Australian sculptor [[Robert Hitchcock]] to create a statue. The result was a life-size statue in [[bronze]], depicting Yagan standing naked with a spear held across his shoulders. Hitchcock's statue of Yagan was officially opened by Yagan Committee chairperson Elizabeth Hanson on 11 September 1984. It stands on [[Heirisson Island]] in the [[Swan River (Western Australia)|Swan River]] near Perth.

In 1997, within a week of the return of Yagan's head to Perth, vandals beheaded the statue using an [[angle grinder]]. Soon after a replacement head was installed and it too was detached and stolen. Credit for the act was anonymously claimed by a "British loyalist" as an act of retaliation for Colbung's comments about [[Diana, Princess of Wales]].{{sfn|Fforde|2002|p=239}} The [[Western Australia Police]] did not succeed in identifying the vandals, nor in recovering the heads, and deemed it infeasible to have the statue fenced off or placed under guard.<ref name="Phillips 1998">{{cite journal | year = 1998 | title = Western Australia: July to December 1977 | journal=[[Australian Journal of Politics & History]] | volume = 44 | issue = 2 | pages = 270–285 | doi = 10.1111/1467-8497.00018 | author=[[Harry C. J. Phillips|Phillips, Harry]] |author2=Black, David |authorlink2=David Black (historian) }}</ref>

Commentary on the beheadings varied widely. One column in ''The West Australia'' found humour in them, referring to the head as a "bonce" and a "noggin", and finished with a pun on "skullduggery".<ref name="Muecke 2004"/> Stephen Muecke calls this the "satirical trivialising of Aboriginal concerns";<ref name="Muecke 2004">{{cite book | first = Stephen | last = Muecke | year = 2004 |pages=39–42 |title = Ancient and Modern: Time, Culture and Indigenous Philosophy | publisher=UNSW Press | isbn = 0-86840-786-0}}</ref> and Adam Shoemaker writes "This is the stuff of light humour and comic relief. There is no sense of the decapitation as being an act of vandalism, even less that it could have been motivated by malevolence&nbsp;... [T]he piece has a definite authorising function".<ref name="Shoemaker 2000">{{cite journal | first = Adam | last = Shoemaker | year = 2000 | title = The Headless State | journal=Griffith Law Review | volume = 9 | issue = 2 | pages = 358–370}}</ref> On the other hand, academic analysis has treated the act with much more gravity. In 2007, for example, David Martin described the decapitation as "an act which speaks not only to the continuance of white settler racism, but also to the power of mimesis to invigorate our modern memorials and monuments with a life of their own."<ref name="Martin 2007">{{cite journal | first = David | last = Martin | year = 2007 | title = Of monuments and masks: historiography in the time of curiosity's ruin | journal=Postcolonial studies | volume = 10 | issue = 3 | pages = 311–320 | doi = 10.1080/13688790701488197}}</ref>

In 2002, [[Member of the Western Australian Legislative Assembly]] [[Janet Woollard]] called for the statue's [[intimate part|genitalia]] to be covered up, but nothing was done. In November 2005 Richard Wilkes again called for the statue's groin to be covered, on the grounds that such a depiction would be more historically accurate, as Yagan would have worn a covering for most of the year. Also under consideration is the creation of a new statue with a head shape that accords better with the forensic reconstruction of Yagan's head.<ref name="Kent 2005">Kent, Melissa (2005). Yagan centre of cover-up bid. ''[[The West Australian]]'', 24 November 2005.</ref>

===Literature and film===
<!-- FAIR USE of Yagan of the Bibbulmun cover.jpg: see image description page at http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Image:Yagan_of_the_Bibbulmun_cover.jpg for rationale -->
[[Image:Yagan of the Bibbulmun cover.png|thumb|right|Cover of [[Mary Durack]]'s 1976 children's novel ''Yagan of the Bibbulmun'', with illustrations by [[Revel Cooper]]]]
[[Mary Durack]] published a fictionalised account of Yagan's life in her 1964 children's novel ''The Courteous Savage: Yagan of the Swan River'',<ref name="Durack 1964">{{cite book|authorlink=Mary Durack|last=Durack|first= Mary|year=1964|title=Courteous Savage: Yagan of the Swan River|location=West Melbourne, Victoria | publisher=Thomas Nelson (Australia) Limited}}</ref> which was renamed ''Yagan of the Bibbulmun'' on reissue in 1976.<ref name="Durack 1976">{{cite book|last=Durack|first= Mary|year=1976|title=Yagan of the Bibbulmun|location=West Melbourne, Victoria | publisher=Thomas Nelson (Australia) Limited|isbn=0-17-001996-9}}</ref>

The repeated beheading of Yagan's statue in 1997 prompted Aboriginal writer [[Archie Weller]] to write a short story entitled ''Confessions of a Headhunter''. Weller later worked with film director Sally Riley to adapt the story into a script,<ref name="Riley 1999">{{cite book|author=Riley, Sally and [[Archie Weller|Weller, Archie]]|year=1999|title=Confessions of a Headhunter|location=Surrey Hills, New South Wales|publisher=Scarlett Pictures}}</ref> and in 2000 a 35-minute movie, also named ''Confessions of a Headhunter'', was released.<ref name="AFC">{{cite web|publisher=Australian Film Commission |title=Confessions of a Headhunter|url=http://www.afc.gov.au/filmsandawards/filmdbsearch.aspx?view=title&title=CONFHE|accessdate=19 January 2006|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070926223202/http://www.afc.gov.au/filmsandawards/filmdbsearch.aspx?view=title&title=CONFHE |archivedate = 26 September 2007|deadurl=yes}}</ref> Directed by Sally Riley, the movie won Best Short Fiction Film at the 2000 [[Australian Film Institute Awards|AFI Awards]].<ref>{{cite web|title=AFI Past Winners: 2000 Winners & Nominees|url=http://www.aacta.org/winners-nominees/2000-2010/2000.aspx| publisher=[[Australian Film Institute]] |accessdate=25 January 2016}}</ref> The following year the script won the Script Award in the 2001 [[Western Australian Premier's Book Awards]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://aso.gov.au/titles/shorts/confessions-headhunter/notes/ |title=Confessions of a Headhunter (2000) curator's notes on ASO – Australia's audio and visual heritage online |publisher=Aso.gov.au |accessdate=10 July 2010}}</ref>

In 2002, the South African-born Australian poet [[John Mateer]] published his fourth collection of poems, entitled ''Loanwords''.<ref name="Mateer 2002">{{cite book|author=Mateer, John|year=2002|title=Loanwords|location=Fremantle, Western Australia | publisher=Fremantle Arts Centre Press|isbn=1-86368-359-3|authorlink=John Mateer}}</ref> The collection is divided into four sections, of which the third, ''In the Presence of a Severed Head'', has Yagan as its subject.<ref>{{cite journal|title=J. Mateer, Loanwords |author=Danta, Chris |publisher=[[Monash University]] |work=Colloquy |issue=7 |date=May 2003 |url=http://colloquy.monash.edu.au/issue007/danta.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090930113942/http://www.colloquy.monash.edu.au/issue007/danta.html|archivedate=30 September 2009}}</ref>

===Other cultural references===
A section of ''Kullark'', a play by [[Jack Davis (playwright)|Jack Davis]], explores the deteriorating relationship between Yagan and a settler couple.

In September 1989 an early maturing cultivar of [[barley]], bred by the Western Australian Department of Agriculture for performance on sandy soils, was released under the name "''Hordeum vulgare'' (Barley) c.v. Yagan".<ref name="Portman 1989">{{cite journal | last = Portman | first = P. | year = 1989 | title = Register of Australian Winter Cereal Cultivars. Hordeum vulgare (Barley) cv. Yagan | journal=Australian Journal of Experimental Agriculture | volume = 29 | issue = 1 | page = 143 | doi = 10.1071/EA9890143 | last2 = Portmann | first2 = P }}</ref> Commonly referred to simply as "Yagan", the cultivar is named for Yagan, continuing a tradition of labelling Western Australian grain cultivars after historic people of Western Australia.

